      "beast_baseline": "hey, i'm building a tool to detect DDoS attacks by looking at the entropy of IP addresses in our logs. if the entropy drops or spikes weirdly, it probably means an attack.\n\ncan u write a python function `calculate_ip_entropy(ip_list)` that takes a list of IP strings and returns the Shannon entropy? \n\ni need it to be pretty precise but i'm running tests against a reference script that rounds to 2 decimal places, so make sure it works with these:\n\n```python\nimport math\n\ndef calculate_ip_entropy(ip_list):\n    # your code here\n    pass\n\ndef test_entropy():\n    # Test 1: Uniform distribution\n    ips1 = [\"192.168.1.1\", \"10.0.0.1\", \"172.16.0.1\", \"192.168.1.2\"]\n    # Expected entropy for 4 unique items: log2(4) = 2.0\n    assert round(calculate_ip_entropy(ips1), 2) == 2.0\n    \n    # Test 2: Low entropy (mostly one IP)\n    ips2 = [\"192.168.1.1\", \"192.168.1.1\", \"192.168.1.1\", \"10.0.0.5\"]\n    # Probabilities: 0.75 and 0.25\n    # Entropy: -(0.75*log2(0.75) + 0.25*log2(0.25)) approx 0.81\n    assert round(calculate_ip_entropy(ips2), 2) == 0.81\n\n    # Test 3: Large set\n    ips3 = [\"1.1.1.1\"] * 100\n    assert round(calculate_ip_entropy(ips3), 2) == 0.0\n\n    print(\"All tests passed!\")\n\ntest_entropy()\n```\n\nlet me know when it's done.",
